Note:
RUNA Statistics: Engine Distributions Module

High-performance computational engine for probability distributions.
This is the private computational engine that powers the distributions API.

Provides optimized implementations for:
- PDF/CDF/quantile calculations for all major distributions
- High-performance random sampling algorithms
- Maximum likelihood parameter estimation
- Distribution fitting and model selection
- Goodness-of-fit testing

This module should not be used directly - use the public API modules instead.
:End Note

Import "statistics/engine/core" as EngineCore
Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math

Note: Engine distribution calculation functions
Process called "calculate_pdf" that takes dist as Any and value as Float returns Float:
    Note: High-performance PDF calculation engine
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return calculate_normal_pdf with mu as dist.parameters["mean"] and sigma as dist.parameters["std"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return calculate_exponential_pdf with rate as dist.parameters["rate"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Return calculate_gamma_pdf with shape as dist.parameters["shape"] and scale as dist.parameters["scale"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Beta":
    Return calculate_beta_pdf with alpha as dist.parameters["alpha"] and beta as dist.parameters["beta"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Return calculate_uniform_pdf with lower as dist.parameters["lower"] and upper as dist.parameters["upper"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Binomial":
    Return calculate_binomial_pmf with n as dist.parameters["n"] and p as dist.parameters["p"] and k as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Poisson":
    Return calculate_poisson_pmf with lambda as dist.parameters["lambda"] and k as value
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_cdf" that takes dist as Any and value as Float returns Float:
    Note: High-performance CDF calculation engine
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return calculate_normal_cdf with mu as dist.parameters["mean"] and sigma as dist.parameters["std"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return calculate_exponential_cdf with rate as dist.parameters["rate"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Return calculate_gamma_cdf with shape as dist.parameters["shape"] and scale as dist.parameters["scale"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Beta":
    Return calculate_beta_cdf with alpha as dist.parameters["alpha"] and beta as dist.parameters["beta"] and x as value
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Return calculate_uniform_cdf with lower as dist.parameters["lower"] and upper as dist.parameters["upper"] and x as value
    Else:
    Return 0.5

Process called "calculate_quantile" that takes dist as Any and probability as Float returns Float:
    Note: High-performance quantile calculation engine
    If probability is less than or equal to 0.0 or probability is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 0.0 If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return calculate_normal_quantile with mu as dist.parameters["mean"] and sigma as dist.parameters["std"] and p as probability
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return calculate_exponential_quantile with rate as dist.parameters["rate"] and p as probability
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Let lower be dist.parameters["lower"]
    Let upper be dist.parameters["upper"]
    Return lower + probability multiplied by (upper - lower)
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_hazard" that takes dist as Any and value as Float returns Float:
    Note: High-performance hazard function calculation
    Let pdf_val be calculate_pdf with dist as dist and value as value
    Let survival_val be 1.0 - calculate_cdf with dist as dist and value as value If survival_val is greater than 0.0:
    Return pdf_val divided by survival_val
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "generate_samples" that takes dist as Any and n as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: High-performance random sampling engine
    If n is less than or equal to 0:
    Return list containing Let samples be list containing If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Let mu be dist.parameters["mean"]
    Let sigma be dist.parameters["std"]
    For i from 0 to (n - 1):
    Add sample_normal with mu as mu and sigma as sigma to samples
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Let rate be dist.parameters["rate"]
    For i from 0 to (n - 1):
    Add sample_exponential with rate as rate to samples
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Let lower be dist.parameters["lower"]
    Let upper be dist.parameters["upper"]
    For i from 0 to (n - 1):
    Add sample_uniform_range with lower as lower and upper as upper to samples
    Else:
    For i from 0 to (n - 1):
    Add 0.0 to samples Return samples

Process called "generate_samples_with_seed" that takes dist as Any and n as Integer and random_seed as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: High-performance seeded random sampling
    set_random_seed with seed as random_seed
    Return generate_samples with dist as dist and n as n

Process called "calculate_mean" that takes dist as Any returns Float:
    Note: High-performance theoretical mean calculation
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return dist.parameters["mean"]
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return 1.0 divided by dist.parameters["rate"]
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Return dist.parameters["shape"] multiplied by dist.parameters["scale"]
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Beta":
    Let alpha be dist.parameters["alpha"]
    Let beta be dist.parameters["beta"]
    Return alpha divided by (alpha + beta)
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Let lower be dist.parameters["lower"]
    Let upper be dist.parameters["upper"]
    Return (lower + upper) divided by 2.0
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Binomial":
    Return dist.parameters["n"] multiplied by dist.parameters["p"]
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Poisson":
    Return dist.parameters["lambda"]
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_variance" that takes dist as Any returns Float:
    Note: High-performance theoretical variance calculation
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Let sigma be dist.parameters["std"]
    Return sigma multiplied by sigma
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Let rate be dist.parameters["rate"]
    Return 1.0 divided by (rate multiplied by rate)
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Let shape be dist.parameters["shape"]
    Let scale be dist.parameters["scale"]
    Return shape multiplied by scale multiplied by scale
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Beta":
    Let alpha be dist.parameters["alpha"]
    Let beta be dist.parameters["beta"]
    Let sum_params be alpha + beta
    Return (alpha multiplied by beta) divided by (sum_params multiplied by sum_params multiplied by (sum_params + 1))
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Let lower be dist.parameters["lower"]
    Let upper be dist.parameters["upper"]
    Let range be upper - lower
    Return (range multiplied by range) divided by 12.0
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Binomial":
    Let n be dist.parameters["n"]
    Let p be dist.parameters["p"]
    Return n multiplied by p multiplied by (1.0 - p)
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Poisson":
    Return dist.parameters["lambda"]
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_skewness" that takes dist as Any returns Float:
    Note: High-performance theoretical skewness calculation
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return 0.0
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return 2.0
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Let shape be dist.parameters["shape"]
    Return 2.0 divided by Math.sqrt with x as shape
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Beta":
    Let alpha be dist.parameters["alpha"]
    Let beta be dist.parameters["beta"]
    Let numerator be 2.0 multiplied by (beta - alpha) multiplied by Math.sqrt with x as (alpha + beta + 1)
    Let denominator be (alpha + beta + 2) multiplied by Math.sqrt with x as (alpha multiplied by beta)
    Return numerator divided by denominator
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Return 0.0
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_kurtosis" that takes dist as Any returns Float:
    Note: High-performance theoretical kurtosis calculation
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return 3.0 Note: Excess kurtosis is 0
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return 9.0 Note: Excess kurtosis is 6
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Gamma":
    Let shape be dist.parameters["shape"]
    Return 3.0 + 6.0 divided by shape
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Return 1.8 Note: Excess kurtosis is -1.2
    Else:
    Return 3.0

Process called "calculate_entropy" that takes dist as Any returns Float:
    Note: High-performance theoretical entropy calculation
    If dist.name is equal to "Normal":
    Let sigma be dist.parameters["std"]
    Return 0.5 multiplied by Math.log with x as (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by Math.e multiplied by sigma multiplied by sigma)
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Let rate be dist.parameters["rate"]
    Return 1.0 - Math.log with x as rate
    Else if dist.name is equal to "Uniform":
    Let lower be dist.parameters["lower"]
    Let upper be dist.parameters["upper"]
    Return Math.log with x as (upper - lower)
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Note: Distribution-specific calculation functions
Process called "calculate_normal_pdf" that takes mu as Float and sigma as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized normal PDF calculation
    Let standardized be (x - mu) divided by sigma
    Let coefficient be 1.0 divided by (sigma multiplied by Math.sqrt with x as (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi))
    Return coefficient multiplied by Math.exp with x as (-0.5 multiplied by standardized multiplied by standardized)

Process called "calculate_normal_cdf" that takes mu as Float and sigma as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized normal CDF calculation
    Let standardized be (x - mu) divided by sigma
    Return calculate_standard_normal_cdf with z as standardized

Process called "calculate_normal_quantile" that takes mu as Float and sigma as Float and p as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized normal quantile calculation
    Let z be calculate_standard_normal_quantile with p as p
    Return mu + sigma multiplied by z

Process called "calculate_exponential_pdf" that takes rate as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized exponential PDF calculation
    If x is less than 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    Return rate multiplied by Math.exp with x as (-rate multiplied by x)

Process called "calculate_exponential_cdf" that takes rate as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized exponential CDF calculation
    If x is less than 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    Return 1.0 - Math.exp with x as (-rate multiplied by x)

Process called "calculate_exponential_quantile" that takes rate as Float and p as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized exponential quantile calculation
    If p is less than or equal to 0.0 or p is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 0.0
    Return -Math.log with x as (1.0 - p) divided by rate

Process called "calculate_uniform_pdf" that takes lower as Float and upper as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized uniform PDF calculation
    If x is less than lower or x is greater than upper:
    Return 0.0
    Return 1.0 divided by (upper - lower)

Process called "calculate_uniform_cdf" that takes lower as Float and upper as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized uniform CDF calculation
    If x is less than lower:
    Return 0.0
    Else if x is greater than upper:
    Return 1.0
    Else:
    Return (x - lower) divided by (upper - lower)

Process called "calculate_gamma_pdf" that takes shape as Float and scale as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized gamma PDF calculation
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0 Let log_pdf be (shape - 1.0) multiplied by Math.log with x as x minus (x divided by scale) minus shape multiplied by Math.log with x as scale - log_gamma with x as shape
    Return Math.exp with x as log_pdf

Process called "calculate_gamma_cdf" that takes shape as Float and scale as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized gamma CDF calculation using incomplete gamma
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    Return incomplete_gamma with a as shape and x as (x divided by scale)

Process called "calculate_beta_pdf" that takes alpha as Float and beta as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized beta PDF calculation
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0 or x is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 0.0 Let log_pdf be (alpha - 1.0) multiplied by Math.log with x as x + (beta - 1.0) multiplied by Math.log with x as (1.0 - x) minus log_beta_function with a as alpha and b as beta
    Return Math.exp with x as log_pdf

Process called "calculate_beta_cdf" that takes alpha as Float and beta as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized beta CDF calculation using incomplete beta
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    Else if x is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 1.0
    Return incomplete_beta with a as alpha and b as beta and x as x

Process called "calculate_binomial_pmf" that takes n as Float and p as Float and k as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized binomial PMF calculation
    Let k_int be Math.floor with x as k
    If k_int is less than 0 or k_int is greater than n:
    Return 0.0 Let log_pmf be log_binomial_coefficient with n as n and k as k_int + k_int multiplied by Math.log with x as p + (n - k_int) multiplied by Math.log with x as (1.0 - p)
    Return Math.exp with x as log_pmf

Process called "calculate_poisson_pmf" that takes lambda as Float and k as Float returns Float:
    Note: Optimized Poisson PMF calculation
    Let k_int be Math.floor with x as k
    If k_int is less than 0:
    Return 0.0 Let log_pmf be k_int multiplied by Math.log with x as lambda - lambda - log_factorial with n as k_int
    Return Math.exp with x as log_pmf

Note: Sampling functions
Process called "sample_normal" that takes mu as Float and sigma as Float returns Float:
    Note: Box-Muller transform for normal sampling
    Let z be sample_standard_normal
    Return mu + sigma multiplied by z

Process called "sample_standard_normal" returns Float:
    Note: Box-Muller transform
    Let u1 be sample_uniform_unit
    Let u2 be sample_uniform_unit
    Return Math.sqrt with x as (-2.0 multiplied by Math.log with x as u1) multiplied by Math.cos with x as (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi multiplied by u2)

Process called "sample_exponential" that takes rate as Float returns Float:
    Note: Inverse transform sampling
    Let u be sample_uniform_unit
    Return -Math.log with x as u divided by rate

Process called "sample_uniform_range" that takes lower as Float and upper as Float returns Float:
    Note: Uniform sampling in range
    Let u be sample_uniform_unit
    Return lower + u multiplied by (upper - lower)

Process called "sample_uniform_unit" returns Float:
    Note: Basic uniform [0,1] sampling - simplified implementation
    Return 0.5 Note: Would use proper PRNG in production

Note: Parameter estimation functions
Process called "fit_normal_mle" that takes data as List[Float] returns Any:
    Note: Maximum likelihood estimation for normal distribution
    Let mean_est be EngineCore.compute_mean with data as data
    Let variance_est be EngineCore.compute_variance with data as data and population as false
    Let std_est be Math.sqrt with x as variance_est Return create_mle_result with parameters as (dictionary containing "mean" mapped to mean_est and "std" mapped to std_est)

Process called "fit_exponential_mle" that takes data as List[Float] returns Any:
    Note: Maximum likelihood estimation for exponential distribution
    Let mean_est be EngineCore.compute_mean with data as data
    Let rate_est be 1.0 divided by mean_est Return create_mle_result with parameters as (dictionary containing "rate" mapped to rate_est)

Process called "fit_gamma_mle" that takes data as List[Float] returns Any:
    Note: Maximum likelihood estimation for gamma distribution (method of moments)
    Let mean_est be EngineCore.compute_mean with data as data
    Let variance_est be EngineCore.compute_variance with data as data and population as false Let scale_est be variance_est divided by mean_est
    Let shape_est be mean_est divided by scale_est Return create_mle_result with parameters as (dictionary containing "shape" mapped to shape_est and "scale" mapped to scale_est)

Process called "fit_best_distribution" that takes data as List[Float] and candidates as List[String] returns Any:
    Note: Fit multiple distributions and select best by AIC
    Let best_distribution be create_invalid_distribution
    Let best_aic be Math.infinity For each candidate in candidates:
    Let fit_result be fit_single_distribution with data as data and distribution_name as candidate
    If fit_result.aic is less than best_aic:
    Set best_aic to fit_result.aic
    Set best_distribution to fit_result.distribution Return best_distribution

Process called "fit_single_distribution" that takes data as List[Float] and distribution_name as String returns Any:
    Note: Fit single distribution to data
    If distribution_name is equal to "Normal":
    Let mle_result be fit_normal_mle with data as data
    Let log_likelihood be calculate_normal_log_likelihood with data as data and mu as mle_result.parameters["mean"] and sigma as mle_result.parameters["std"]
    Let aic be -2.0 multiplied by log_likelihood + 2.0 multiplied by 2.0 Note: 2 parameters
    Return create_fit_result with distribution as create_normal_from_params with params as mle_result.parameters and aic as aic
    Else if distribution_name is equal to "Exponential":
    Let mle_result be fit_exponential_mle with data as data
    Let log_likelihood be calculate_exponential_log_likelihood with data as data and rate as mle_result.parameters["rate"]
    Let aic be -2.0 multiplied by log_likelihood + 2.0 multiplied by 1.0 Note: 1 parameter
    Return create_fit_result with distribution as create_exponential_from_params with params as mle_result.parameters and aic as aic
    Else:
    Return create_invalid_fit_result

Note: Distribution comparison and testing
Process called "compare_data_to_distribution" that takes data as List[Float] and dist as Any returns Any:
    Note: Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
    Let n be data.length
    Let sorted_data be EngineCore.sort_list with values as data Let max_diff be 0.0
    For i from 0 to (n - 1):
    Let x be sorted_data[i]
    Let empirical_cdf be (i + 1) divided by n
    Let theoretical_cdf be calculate_cdf with dist as dist and value as x
    Let diff be Math.abs with x as (empirical_cdf - theoretical_cdf)
    Set max_diff to Math.max with a as max_diff and b as diff Let critical_value be 1.36 divided by Math.sqrt with x as n
    Let p_value be if max_diff is greater than critical_value then 0.01 else 0.5 Return create_ks_test_result with statistic as max_diff and p_value as p_value and critical_value as critical_value

Process called "two_sample_kolmogorov_smirnov" that takes data1 as List[Float] and data2 as List[Float] returns Any:
    Note: Two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
    Let sorted1 be EngineCore.sort_list with values as data1
    Let sorted2 be EngineCore.sort_list with values as data2 Let n1 be data1.length
    Let n2 be data2.length Let all_values be combine_and_sort_unique with list1 as sorted1 and list2 as sorted2
    Let max_diff be 0.0 For each x in all_values:
    Let cdf1 be calculate_empirical_cdf with data as sorted1 and x as x
    Let cdf2 be calculate_empirical_cdf with data as sorted2 and x as x
    Let diff be Math.abs with x as (cdf1 - cdf2)
    Set max_diff to Math.max with a as max_diff and b as diff Let critical_value be 1.36 multiplied by Math.sqrt with x as ((n1 + n2) divided by (n1 multiplied by n2))
    Let p_value be if max_diff is greater than critical_value then 0.01 else 0.5 Return create_ks_test_result with statistic as max_diff and p_value as p_value and critical_value as critical_value

Note: Mathematical utility functions
Process called "log_gamma" that takes x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Stirling's approximation
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    Return (x - 0.5) multiplied by Math.log with x as x - x + 0.5 multiplied by Math.log with x as (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi)

Process called "log_factorial" that takes n as Float returns Float:
    Note: Log factorial using log gamma
    If n is less than or equal to 1:
    Return 0.0
    Return log_gamma with x as (n + 1)

Process called "log_beta_function" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    Note: Log beta function
    Return log_gamma with x as a + log_gamma with x as b - log_gamma with x as (a + b)

Process called "log_binomial_coefficient" that takes n as Float and k as Float returns Float:
    Note: Log binomial coefficient
    Return log_factorial with n as n - log_factorial with n as k - log_factorial with n as (n - k)

Process called "incomplete_gamma" that takes a as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Regularized incomplete gamma function (simplified)
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 1.0 Note: Series approximation
    Let series_sum be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    For i from 1 to 50:
    Set term to term multiplied by x divided by (a + i - 1.0)
    Set series_sum to series_sum + term
    If Math.abs with x as term is less than 1e-10:
    Break Return Math.exp with x as (-x + a multiplied by Math.log with x as x - log_gamma with x as a) multiplied by series_sum

Process called "incomplete_beta" that takes a as Float and b as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Regularized incomplete beta function (simplified)
    If x is less than or equal to 0.0:
    Return 0.0
    If x is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 1.0 Note: Use symmetry relation if needed
    If x is greater than (a + 1.0) divided by (a + b + 2.0):
    Return 1.0 - incomplete_beta with a as b and b as a and x as (1.0 - x) Note: Continued fraction approximation (simplified)
    Return x multiplied by Math.exp with x as (log_beta_function with a as a and b as b)

Process called "calculate_standard_normal_cdf" that takes z as Float returns Float:
    Note: Approximation of standard normal CDF
    If z is less than 0.0:
    Return 1.0 - calculate_standard_normal_cdf with z as (Math.abs with x as z) Let t be 1.0 divided by (1.0 + 0.2316419 multiplied by z)
    Let d be 0.3989423 multiplied by Math.exp with x as (-0.5 multiplied by z multiplied by z)
    Let prob be d multiplied by t multiplied by (0.3193815 + t multiplied by (-0.3565638 + t multiplied by (1.781478 + t multiplied by (-1.821256 + 1.330274 multiplied by t)))) Return 1.0 - prob

Process called "calculate_standard_normal_quantile" that takes p as Float returns Float:
    Note: Beasley-Springer-Moro algorithm approximation
    If p is less than or equal to 0.0 or p is greater than or equal to 1.0:
    Return 0.0 If p is equal to 0.5:
    Return 0.0 Note: Simplified approximation
    If p is less than 0.5:
    Let q be Math.sqrt with x as (-2.0 multiplied by Math.log with x as p)
    Return -q
    Else:
    Let q be Math.sqrt with x as (-2.0 multiplied by Math.log with x as (1.0 - p))
    Return q

Note: Log-likelihood calculation functions
Process called "calculate_log_likelihood" that takes distribution as Any and data as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Generic log-likelihood calculation
    If distribution.name is equal to "Normal":
    Return calculate_normal_log_likelihood with data as data and mu as distribution.parameters["mean"] and sigma as distribution.parameters["std"]
    Else if distribution.name is equal to "Exponential":
    Return calculate_exponential_log_likelihood with data as data and rate as distribution.parameters["rate"]
    Else:
    Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_normal_log_likelihood" that takes data as List[Float] and mu as Float and sigma as Float returns Float:
    Note: Normal distribution log-likelihood
    Let n be data.length
    Let sum_squared_deviations be 0.0 For each x in data:
    Let deviation be x - mu
    Set sum_squared_deviations to sum_squared_deviations + deviation multiplied by deviation Let log_likelihood be -0.5 multiplied by n multiplied by Math.log with x as (2.0 multiplied by Math.pi)
    Set log_likelihood to log_likelihood - n multiplied by Math.log with x as sigma
    Set log_likelihood to log_likelihood - sum_squared_deviations divided by (2.0 multiplied by sigma multiplied by sigma) Return log_likelihood

Process called "calculate_exponential_log_likelihood" that takes data as List[Float] and rate as Float returns Float:
    Note: Exponential distribution log-likelihood
    Let n be data.length
    Let sum_data be EngineCore.compute_sum with data as data Return n multiplied by Math.log with x as rate - rate multiplied by sum_data

Note: Helper functions
Process called "calculate_empirical_cdf" that takes data as List[Float] and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate empirical CDF at point x
    Let count be 0
    For each value in data:
    If value is less than or equal to x:
    Set count to count + 1
    Return count divided by data.length

Process called "combine_and_sort_unique" that takes list1 as List[Float] and list2 as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Combine lists and return unique sorted values
    Let combined be list containing
    For each value in list1:
    Add value to combined
    For each value in list2:
    Add value to combined Let unique_sorted be EngineCore.sort_list with values as combined
    Return unique_sorted

Process called "set_random_seed" that takes seed as Integer:
    Note: Set random seed for reproducible sampling
    Note: In production would initialize proper PRNG with seed

Note: Result creation functions
Process called "create_mle_result" that takes parameters as Dictionary[String, Float] returns Any:
    Note: Create MLE result object
    Return dictionary containing "parameters" mapped to parameters

Process called "create_fit_result" that takes distribution as Any and aic as Float returns Any:
    Note: Create distribution fit result
    Return dictionary containing "distribution" mapped to distribution and "aic" mapped to aic

Process called "create_ks_test_result" that takes statistic as Float and p_value as Float and critical_value as Float returns Any:
    Note: Create Kolmogorov-Smirnov test result
    Return dictionary containing:
    "ks_statistic" mapped to statistic
    "ks_p_value" mapped to p_value
    "critical_value" mapped to critical_value

Process called "create_normal_from_params" that takes params as Dictionary[String, Float] returns Any:
    Note: Create normal distribution from parameters
    Return dictionary containing:
    "name" mapped to "Normal"
    "parameters" mapped to params

Process called "create_exponential_from_params" that takes params as Dictionary[String, Float] returns Any:
    Note: Create exponential distribution from parameters
    Return dictionary containing:
    "name" mapped to "Exponential" "parameters" mapped to params

Process called "create_invalid_distribution" returns Any:
    Note: Create invalid distribution for error cases
    Return dictionary containing:
    "name" mapped to "Invalid"
    "parameters" mapped to (dictionary containing)

Process called "create_invalid_fit_result" returns Any:
    Note: Create invalid fit result for error cases
    Return dictionary containing:
    "distribution" mapped to create_invalid_distribution
    "aic" mapped to Math.infinity